[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] In symbolic programming languages, it is easy to have patterns as arguments to functions or as elements of data structures.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] A consequence of this is the ability to use patterns to declaratively make statements about pieces of data and to flexibly instruct functions how to operate.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] For instance, the Mathematica function `Compile` can be used to make more efficient versions of the code.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] The Curry–Howard correspondence between proofs and programs relates ML-style pattern matching to case analysis and proof by exhaustion.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] By far the most common form of pattern matching involves strings of characters.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] In many programming languages, a particular syntax of strings is used to represent regular expressions, which are patterns describing string characters.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] However, it is possible to perform some string pattern matching within the same framework that has been discussed throughout this article.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] In Mathematica, strings are represented as trees of root StringExpression and all the characters in order as children of the root.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] Thus, to match "any amount of trailing characters", a new wildcard ___ is needed in contrast to _ that would match only a single character.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] In Haskell and functional programming languages in general, strings are represented as functional lists of characters.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] A functional list is defined as an empty list, or an element constructed on an existing list.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] The structure for a list with some elements is thus `element:list`.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] When pattern matching, we assert that a certain piece of data is equal to a certain pattern.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] We assert that the first element of `head`'s argument is called element, and the function returns this.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] We know that this is the first element because of the way lists are defined, a single element constructed onto a list.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] The empty list would not match the pattern at all, as an empty list does not have a head (the first element that is constructed).
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] will match a string that has two characters and begins with "a".
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] Symbolic entities can be introduced to represent many different classes of relevant features of a string.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] will match a string that consists of a letter first, and then a number.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] The main advantage of symbolic string manipulation is that it can be completely integrated with the rest of the programming language, rather than being a separate, special purpose subunit.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] The entire power of the language can be leveraged to build up the patterns themselves or analyze and transform the programs that contain them.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL (*StriNg Oriented and symBOlic Language*) is a computer programming language developed between 1962 and 1967 at AT&T Bell Laboratories by David J.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 stands apart from most programming languages by having patterns as a first-class data type (*i.e.* a data type whose values can be manipulated in all ways permitted to any other data type in the programming language) and by providing operators for pattern concatenation and alternation.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] Strings generated during execution can be treated as programs and executed.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL was quite widely taught in larger US universities in the late 1960s and early 1970s and was widely used in the 1970s and 1980s as a text manipulation language in the humanities.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] Since SNOBOL's creation, newer languages such as AWK and Perl have made string manipulation by means of regular expressions fashionable.
[src:grain-language/pattern-matching] SNOBOL4 patterns, however, subsume Backus–Naur form (BNF) grammars, which are equivalent to context-free grammars and more powerful than regular expressions.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:grain-language/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:grain-language/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:grain-language/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:grain-language/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The main goal of WebAssembly is to facilitate high-performance applications on web pages, but it is also designed to be usable in non-web environments.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] It is an open standard intended to support any language on any operating system, and in practice many of the most popular languages already have at least some level of support.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Announced in 2015 (2015) and first released in March 2017 (2017-03), WebAssembly became a World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) recommendation on 5 December 2019 and it received the *Programming Languages Software Award* from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM) SIGPLAN in 2021.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The W3C maintains the standard with contributions from Mozilla, Microsoft, Google, Apple, Fastly, Intel, and Red Hat.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The name "WebAssembly" is intended to suggest bringing assembly language programming to the World Wide Web, where it will be executed client-side, by the website-user's computer via the user's web browser.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] To accomplish this, WebAssembly must be much more hardware-independent than a true assembly language.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WebAssembly was first announced in 2015, and the first demonstration was executing Unity's *Angry Bots* in Firefox, Google Chrome, and Microsoft Edge [Legacy].
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The precursor technologies were asm.js from Mozilla and Google Native Client, and the initial implementation was based on the feature set of asm.js.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In March 2017, the design of the minimum viable product (MVP) was declared to be finished and the preview phase ended.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In late September 2017, Safari 11 was released with support.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In February 2018, the WebAssembly Working Group published three public working drafts for the Core Specification, JavaScript Interface, and Web API.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The MVP was focused on low-level languages such as C and C++, with the intent to add features useful for high-level languages in a future version.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The WebAssembly 2.0 specification was finished in 2022 and became a W3C standard in December 2024.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] It adds many single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) related instructions and a new v128 datatype, with the ability for functions to return multiple values, mass memory initialize/copy instructions, and reference types, which are opaque pointers to objects outside of the linear memory.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WebAssembly 3.0 was released in September 2025.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] New features include a 64-bit address space, multiple address spaces, exception handling, and garbage collected struct and array types.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Support for garbage collection enables more efficient compiling for high-level languages, but WasmGC from WebAssembly 3.0 lacks the abilities needed by .NET runtime.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] While WebAssembly was initially designed to permit near-native code execution speed in the web browser, it has been considered valuable outside of such, in more generalized contexts.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] A WebAssembly runtime environment is a low-level virtual stack machine, akin to JVM or Flash VM; it can be embedded into any host application, and thus there have been created standalone WebAssembly runtime environments, including Wasmtime , WebAssembly Micro Runtime , Wasmer , WasmEdge and wazero .
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In November 2017, Mozilla declared support "in all major browsers", after WebAssembly was enabled by default in Edge [Legacy] 16.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] This support also includes mobile web browsers for iOS and Android.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] As of March 2024, 99% of tracked web browsers support WebAssembly (version 1.0), more than for its predecessor asm.js.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] For some extensions, from the 2.0 draft standard, support may be lower, but still more than 90% of web browsers may already support, e.g. the reference types extension.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Non-browser WebAssembly runtimes include Wasmer, Wasmtime, WAMR, WAVM, wasm3, and others.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] These systems execute precompiled Wasm modules and often provide additional APIs for embedding WebAssembly in different environments.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Use cases for wasm outside the browser include plug-in interfaces and lightweight virtualization.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WebAssembly implementations generally use either ahead-of-time (AOT) or just-in-time (JIT) compiling, though some may also use an interpreter.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] While the first implementations appeared in web browsers, there are now many non-browser implementations for general-purpose use.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Because WebAssembly executables are precompiled, a variety of programming languages can target Wasm.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Compiling is done either through direct output to Wasm or via intermediate virtual machines implemented in Wasm.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] As of 2021, around 40 programming languages support WebAssembly as a compiling target.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Web browsers prevent WebAssembly code from directly manipulating the Document Object Model.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Wasm code must defer to JavaScript for this.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In an October 2023 survey of developers, less than half of the 303 participants were satisfied with the state of WebAssembly.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] A large majority cited the need for improvement in four areas: § WASI, debugging support, integration with JavaScript and browser APIs, and build tooling.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] All major browsers allow WebAssembly if `Content-Security-Policy` is not specified, or if the value `unsafe-eval` is used, but behave differently otherwise; Chrome *requires* `unsafe-eval`, though a worker thread can be a workaround.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In June 2018, a security researcher presented the possibility of using WebAssembly to circumvent browser mitigations for Spectre and Meltdown security vulnerabilities once support for threads with shared memory is added.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Due to this concern, WebAssembly developers put the feature on hold.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] However, in order to explore these future language extensions, Google Chrome added experimental support for the WebAssembly thread proposal in October 2018.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WebAssembly has been criticized for allowing greater ease of hiding the evidence for malware writers, scammers and phishing attackers; WebAssembly is present on the user's machine only in its compiled form, which "[makes malware] detection difficult".
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Speed and the easy ability to conceal in WebAssembly have led to its use in hidden crypto mining within the website visitor's device.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] An April 2021 study from Universität Stuttgart found that since then crypto mining has been marginalized, falling to below 1% of all WebAssembly modules gathered from a wide range of sources, also including the Alexa top 1 million websites.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] As WebAssembly supports only structured control flow, it is amenable toward security verification techniques including symbolic execution.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In 2019, a group of researchers from the University of Massachusetts Amherst presented a comprehensive analysis of WebAssembly's performance compared to native code.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The paper identified several reasons for this performance difference, including missing optimizations, code generation issues in WebAssembly compilers, and inherent limits of the WebAssembly platform.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In 2022, it was determined by researchers that a Wasm program runs at about 120% of (or 20% faster than) the speed of a comparable JavaScript program.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Those findings align with the experience of a startup company named "Zaplib", whose founders summarized in a blog that it was shutting down due to lack of performance in WebAssembly.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Their goal had been to significantly increase the performance of existing web apps by incrementally porting them to Rust/Wasm; however, porting a customer's simulator from JavaScript yielded only a 5% improvement in performance.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Benchmarking has revealed several other pain-points for WebAssembly, such as poor performance because of no direct access to the DOM, a problem which is being addressed.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WebAssembly System Interface (WASI) is a simple interface (application binary interface (ABI) and application programming interface (API)) designed by Mozilla, which is intended to be portable to any platform.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] It provides features similar to the Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX), such as file input/output (I/O) constrained by capability-based security.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WASI is influenced by CloudABI and Capsicum.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Solomon Hykes, a co-founder of Docker, wrote in 2019, "If WASM+WASI existed in 2008, we wouldn't have needed to create Docker.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WASI 0.1 provides a few POSIX-like APIs such as file I/O, reading environment variables, and random-number generation, but has very little support for networking.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WASI 0.2 is redesigned based on the WebAssembly Component Model.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WASI 0.3 will add support for async functions; the host translates between blocking and async function calls, so an exported function that blocks may be called as an asynchronous function, and vice-versa.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Starting in 0.2, WASI is defined in terms of the component model.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Interfaces in the component model are specified in an IDL called WIT (WebAssembly Interface Types).
[src:grain-language/webassembly] While core wasm only supports integer and floating-point numbers, interfaces in WIT can express types such as strings, lists, and user-defined record and variant types, and are language-agnostic.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Components cannot access each other's memory, and so interact only via imported and exported functions.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The component model is designed around composition: two components can be composed into a single component when the exports of one component match another's imports, allowing any interface to be virtualized.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Interfaces in WIT are grouped together into a "world".
[src:grain-language/webassembly] WASI 0.2 defines a CLI world similar to the POSIX-like API of WASI 0.1, and an HTTP proxy world for web servers.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The component model is not currently supported by browsers.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The general standard provides core specifications for the JavaScript API and details on embedding.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Wasm code (binary code, i.e. bytecode) is intended to be run on a portable virtual stack machine (VM).
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The VM is designed to be faster to parse and execute than JavaScript and to have compact code representation.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Any external functionality (like syscalls) that may be expected by Wasm binary code is not stipulated by the standard; instead, the standard specifies how the host environment can provide such an interface via a "module".
[src:grain-language/webassembly] A Wasm program is designed as a separate module containing collections of various Wasm-defined values and program type definitions.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] These are provided in either binary or textual format (see below) that have a common structure.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Such a module may provide a start function that is executed upon instantiation of a wasm binary.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The list of instruction types includes those for standard memory load/store, numeric, parametric, control flow, and Wasm-specific variables.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The number of opcodes used in the original standard (§ MVP) was a bit fewer than 200 of the 256 possible opcodes.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Subsequent versions of WebAssembly pushed the number of opcodes a bit over 200.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The WebAssembly SIMD proposal (for parallel processing) introduces an alternate opcode prefix (0xfd) for 128-bit wide SIMD instructions; the concatenation of the SIMD prefix, plus an opcode that is valid after the SIMD prefix, forms each SIMD opcode.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] These SIMD opcodes are both portable and intended to map directly to native instruction sets like x86-64 and ARM.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In contrast, SIMD instructions are not directly supported by Java's JVM or .NET's CIL; however, both do have some APIs for parallel processing, which provide SIMD speedups.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] A newer set of "relaxed SIMD" instructions allow for a limited amount of implementation-defined behavior to improve performance.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] In March 2017, the WebAssembly Community Group reached consensus on the initial ("MVP") binary format, JavaScript API, and reference interpreter.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] It defines a WebAssembly binary format (`.wasm`), which is designed to be used by computers, not humans, and a text format that is human-readable (`.wat`), resembling a cross between S-expressions and traditional assembly languages.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The binary format is straightforward and designed to allow streaming compiling, so compiling can begin before the module is finished downloading, and to allow functions to be compiled in parallel.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] All integer constants are encoded using a space-efficient, variable-length LEB128 encoding.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The WebAssembly text format is more canonically written in a folded format using S-expressions.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] For instructions and expressions, this format is purely syntactic sugar and has no behavioral differences with the linear format.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] A module is implicitly generated by the compiler.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The function is referenced by an entry of the type table in the binary, hence a type section and the `type` emitted by the decompiler.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The compiler and decompiler can be accessed online.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Data in memory is stored in a large, growable array of bytes termed a *linear memory*.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Linear memory is separate from the wasm module's call stack and code and the engine's memory.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] This allows running wasm code in the same process as the JavaScript virtual machine it's embedded in without violating memory safety.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] A module contains a list of global variables separate from linear memory, which may be mutable or immutable.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Functions declare a list of local variables.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] A function's parameters are also local variables.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Instructions operate on a stack of values.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The stack layout is fixed (branches must push and pop the same number of operands), so wasm engines can compile the stack away, producing efficient machine code operations on registers, rather than managing a stack at runtime.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] A stack machine architecture was chosen as it can have higher code density than a register machine.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Unlike typical assembly languages, wasm only uses structured control flow similar to high-level programming languages.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The intentional lack of support for jump instructions makes it simple to validate and compile wasm code in a single pass, and makes it easier to read code disassembled into the text format.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Blocks are delimited with the `block`, `loop`, and `if`/`else` constructs.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Branch instructions contain a label that identifies the depth of a block it is nested in: `br 0` will branch to the block the instruction is contained in, `br 1` will branch to the block that block is contained in, and so on.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Branches to a `block` or `if` jump to the end of the block like a break statement, while branches to a `loop` jump back to the *beginning* of the loop, similar to a continue statement.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] The `br_table` instruction takes an input index and jumps to a target from a list of labels.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] A C-style switch statement can be expressed with a `br_table` inside a series of nested blocks.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Compilers targeting wasm convert unstructured control flow into high-level loops using Emscripten's Relooper algorithm, originally designed to target JavaScript.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Function declarations are listed in a separate section before the section containing the function bodies.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Function pointers are emulated using an index into the global functions table, since code is not inside the linear memory.
[src:grain-language/webassembly] Functions can also be imported and exported, providing the foreign function interface to communicate with JavaScript or other embedders.
